  "prompt": "Are you actually supposed to break people's ribs when performing CPR?",
  "response": "When performing CPR, especially on adults, it is possible to break ribs due to the force and depth of the chest compressions. Effective chest compressions require pushing hard and deep\u2014about 2 to 2.4 inches (5 to 6 centimeters) in depth\u2014and at a rate of 100 to 120 compressions per minute. This force is necessary to create enough pressure to circulate blood throughout the body.\n\nWhile breaking ribs is not the intended outcome, it can happen, and it is more important to focus on the effectiveness of the compressions during an emergency. Proper CPR can be lifesaving, and the priority is to maintain blood circulation and oxygenation until professional medical help arrives. If a rib does break, it is generally better to continue CPR rather than stopping, as the priority is to preserve life.",
